---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="How to Use Docker Containers as Instant SSH Development Environments" description="Step-by-step tutorial: use Docker containers as throwaway SSH dev environments with Sandbox CLI. Install, connect, code, disconnect, done.">
  <article class="blog-post">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="post-header">
        <time class="post-date">2026-04-02</time>
        <h1 class="post-title">How to Use Docker Containers as Instant SSH Development Environments</h1>
        <p class="post-meta">6 min read</p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-body">
        <p>
          Docker containers are perfect for throwaway development environments. But the default workflow -- writing a Dockerfile, running <code>docker exec</code>, dealing with TTY quirks -- is clunky for quick sessions.
        </p>
        <p>
          In this tutorial, I'll show you how to use <a href="/fixitdev-site/tools/sandbox-cli">Sandbox CLI</a> to turn Docker containers into instant SSH development environments. One command in, one command out, auto-cleanup.
        </p>

        <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Docker Desktop or Docker Engine running on your machine</li>
          <li>macOS or Linux (Windows WSL2 works too)</li>
          <li>5 minutes</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Step 1: Install Sandbox CLI</h2>
        <p>The fastest way is Homebrew:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> brew install fixitdev/tap/sandbox</pre>
        <p>Or if you have Go installed:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> go install github.com/mvtrdmqv88-droid/sandbox-cli@latest</pre>
        <p>Verify the install:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> sandbox version
<span class="code-output">sandbox-cli v1.0.0</span></pre>

        <h2>Step 2: Start the Daemon</h2>
        <p>Sandbox CLI uses a lightweight Go daemon to manage containers. Start it:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> sandbox daemon start
<span class="code-output">Daemon started (PID 12345)</span></pre>
        <p>
          The daemon runs in the background and uses minimal resources. It talks to the Docker SDK to create containers and sets up SSH access for each one.
        </p>

        <h2>Step 3: SSH Into a Fresh Container</h2>
        <p>This is where the magic happens:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> sandbox ssh
<span class="code-output">Creating container sandbox-a1b2... done</span>
<span class="code-output">Starting SSH server... done</span>
<span class="code-output">Connecting...</span>

<span class="code-prompt">root@sandbox-a1b2:~#</span></pre>
        <p>
          You're now inside a fresh Ubuntu container. It has common dev tools pre-installed: git, curl, wget, build-essential, Node.js, Python 3. It's a real SSH session, so your terminal works exactly as you'd expect -- tab completion, vim keybindings, everything.
        </p>

        <h2>Step 4: Do Your Work</h2>
        <p>Use it like any Linux machine:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">root@sandbox-a1b2:~#</span> git clone https://github.com/yourproject/repo.git
<span class="code-prompt">root@sandbox-a1b2:~#</span> cd repo && npm install
<span class="code-prompt">root@sandbox-a1b2:~#</span> npm run dev
<span class="code-output">Server running on http://localhost:3000</span></pre>
        <p>
          Need to install something? Go ahead. It's a throwaway environment. <code>apt-get install whatever-you-want</code> without a second thought.
        </p>

        <h2>Step 5: Disconnect</h2>
        <p>When you're done, just exit:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">root@sandbox-a1b2:~#</span> exit
<span class="code-output">Connection closed.</span>
<span class="code-output">Container sandbox-a1b2 destroyed.</span></pre>
        <p>
          The container is gone. All the packages you installed, all the files you created, all the config changes you made -- cleaned up automatically.
        </p>

        <h2>Useful Options</h2>

        <h3>Mount a local directory</h3>
        <p>Need to work on local files inside the container?</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> sandbox ssh --volume ./myproject:/workspace</pre>
        <p>Your local <code>./myproject</code> is now available at <code>/workspace</code> inside the container. Changes persist on your host machine even after the container is destroyed.</p>

        <h3>Use a custom image</h3>
        <p>Don't want Ubuntu? Use any Docker image:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> sandbox ssh --image node:20-slim</pre>

        <h3>Check active sessions</h3>
        <p>See what's running:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> sandbox ls
<span class="code-output">ID              IMAGE           STATUS    UPTIME</span>
<span class="code-output">sandbox-a1b2    ubuntu:latest   running   12m</span>
<span class="code-output">sandbox-c3d4    node:20-slim    running   3m</span></pre>

        <h3>Web Dashboard</h3>
        <p>Prefer a visual overview? Sandbox CLI ships with a Next.js dashboard:</p>
        <pre class="code-block"><span class="code-prompt">$</span> sandbox dashboard
<span class="code-output">Dashboard running at http://localhost:9090</span></pre>
        <p>You'll see active containers, session history, and resource usage at a glance.</p>

        <h2>Free vs Pro</h2>
        <p>
          The free tier gives you 3 containers per day with 30-minute sessions. That's enough for quick experiments and tutorials.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you're using Sandbox CLI as part of your daily workflow, the Pro plan ($4.99/month) removes all limits: unlimited containers, no time restrictions.
        </p>

        <h2>Wrapping Up</h2>
        <p>
          That's the whole workflow. Install, <code>sandbox ssh</code>, code, exit, gone. No Dockerfiles to write, no docker-compose to manage, no cleanup to remember.
        </p>
        <p>
          I built <a href="/fixitdev-site/tools/sandbox-cli">Sandbox CLI</a> because I was tired of polluting my laptop with tools I only needed once. If that sounds familiar, give it a try.
        </p>

        <div class="post-cta">
          <a href="/fixitdev-site/tools/sandbox-cli" class="cta-link">Install Sandbox CLI -- one command to a fresh dev environment</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
